1#!/usr/bin/perl
2## pythonizer -- Translator of the subset of Perl 5 to Python 3.8+
3## Copyright Nikolai Bezroukov, 2019-2022.  Significant updates by Joe Cool (http://github.com/snoopyjc).
4## Licensed under Perl Artistic license
5##
6## Automatic translation of most perl scripts to python 3.8+.
7## Best works for Perl 4 subset of Perl 5 which typically is used in sysadmin scripts.
8## Perl scripts that extensivly use references or OO require more extensive manual effort
9##
10## --- INVOCATION:
11##
12##   pythonizer [options] [file_to_process]
13##
14##--- OPTIONS:
15##    -v -- verbosity 0 -minimal (only serious messages) 3 max verbosity (warning, errors and serious); default -v 1
16##    -h -- this help
17##    -t -- size of tab in the generated Python code (emulated with spaces). Default is 4
18##    -k -- run the Python Black code formatter (if it's available) on the generated python code (default)
19##    -K -- Turn off -k
20##    -l -- the output line length - how many characters per line to generate by the Black code formatter (default 98)
21##    -m -- Make global variables into "my" filescope variables, else they use a separate global namespace
22##    -M -- Turn off -m
23##    NOTE: If neither -m nor -M are passed, the pythonizer uses heuristics to make a best guess here.
24##    -u -- Replace usage strings of the form "Usage: filename.pl ..." with "Usage: filename.py ..." (default)
25##    -U -- Turn off -u
26##    -s -- Attempt to run standard library functions thru pythonizer for use/require - not recommended!
27##    -S -- Turn off -s
28##    -p -- "import perllib" library instead of including functions inline to emulate perl built-in functions (default)
29##    -P -- Turn off -p
30##    -A -- Imply "use autodie qw(:all);"
31##    -T -- Perform a traceback in the generated code on errors
32##    -n -- Trace Run: Generate code to trace subprocess.run results - used in qx, `backtick`, open('|'), and system()
33##    -o dir -- Output directory for .py and .data files, created if need be (defaults to the same location as the input file)
34##    -V -- Imply "no autovivification qw(fetch delete exists store strict);"
35##    -w -- the width of the screen on which you plan to view the protocol of translation. The default is 188.
36##    -R -- remap comma separated list of variables: variables specified as var or *var will map all variables named 'var',
37##          $var will just map scalar to var_v, @var will just map array to var_a, %var will just map hash to var_h,
38##          :global will remap all global vars (default), :all will remap all variables, :none will remap no variables.
39##    -a -- Add __author__, __email__, and __version__ strings to the generated code
40##    -d    level of debugging  default is 0 -- production mode
41##          0 -- Production mode
42##          1 -- Testing mode. Program is autosaved in Archive (primitive versioning mechanism)
43##          2 -- Stop at the beginning of statement analysys (the statement can be selected via breakpoint option -b )
44##          3 -- More debugging output.
45##          4 -- Stop at lexical scanner with $DB::single = 1;
46##          5 -- output stages of Python line generation
47##    -B N  -- for internal debugging - set breakpoint when processing input line N in the first pass
48##    -b N  -- for internal debugging - set breakpoint when processing input line N in the second pass
49##
50##    If -m and -M are both NOT present, you may set these options and all other options in the
51##    perl source file using a special comment of the form "# pragma pythonizer -flags".  You can also
52##    spell the options out optionally prefixed by "no", like "# pragma pythonizer no implicit global my, traceback".
53##--- PARAMETERS:
54##
55##    1st -- full pathname of file (only one argument accepted)
56##
57##--- OUTPUT:
58##    filename.py will be generated in the same folder as the input file
59

2075sub fix_type_issues
2076# Fixup issues with variable types and how perl automatically converts things to the proper type e.g.
2077# strings used in numeric contexts.  This is a recursive function, and returns the adjustment factor
2078# of how many tokens we added.  It uses the functions _num(), _str(), and _int() to make the conversions.
2079# _int() is used in subscripts.  We make use of the type information we gathered in pass 1 to see
2080# if we can eliminate as many of these conversions as possible.  FIXME: As a desired enhancement, we
2081# should "peephole optimize" the code, which means keeping track of the exact type of each variable
2082# in assignment statements in each basic block of code, so that if you say "$j = 1", we know that
2083# "$j" is an int in the same block even if it gets set to a string elsewhere. Once we hit a merge
2084# point, e.g. a "}", then all bets are off!
